Scolopendras, similar to terrestrials, which they call centipedes, when they have devoured the hook, vomit up everything inside until they have used the hook, and then regurgitate it. but sea-foxes are similar in
in danger they swallow further down to the weak line, by which they are easily gnawed. he who is called a granis bites more cautiously
he does not devour the hooks, but spoils the bait. The ram is fattened like a thief, and now, hidden by the shadow of the great ships standing in the sea, he waits, if the pleasure of swimming invites him;
